SIMPLE: shrive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shrive
<hw>Shrive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Shrived</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Shrove</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Shriven</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or
<conjf>Shrived</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shriving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>shriven</ets>,
<ets>schriven</ets>, AS. <ets>scr⟦imac⟧van</ets> to shrive, to impose
penance or punishment; akin to OFries. <ets>skr⟦imac⟧va</ets> to impose
punishment; cf. OS. bi<ets>skr⟦imac⟧ban</ets> to be troubled. Cf.
<er>Shrift</er>, <er>Shrovetide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hear or
receive the confession of; to administer confession and absolution to;
-- said of a priest as the agent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That they should <qex>shrive</qex> their parishioners.</q>
<rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Doubtless he <qex>shrives</qex> this woman, . . . ⟦br⟧
Else ne'er could he so long protract his speech.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till my guilty soul be <qex>shriven</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To confess, and receive absolution; -- used
reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Get you to the church and <qex>shrive</qex> yourself.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shrive
<hw>Shrive</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To receive confessions, as a
priest; to administer confession and absolution.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shrivel</ent>⟦br⟧
